Raw dev notes -- Dashboard Polish & Data Deep Dive

This past week was a whirlwind on the shipping tracking dashboard project. The whole point of this thing is to give users a clear, actionable view of their shipping logistics – where things are, how much they're spending, and crucially, where they can save money. It's all about turning raw shipping data into insights for better decision-making and supply chain optimization.

I spent a good chunk of time really digging into the core logic. We finally got the annual savings calculations dialed in, which involved merging some redundant recommendations that were just cluttering things up. That felt good, like cleaning out a dusty corner of the brain. On the data front, I updated the pricelist rates to reflect the current contracts and added some much-needed clarity between billed vs. list pricing – that's a detail that can really trip people up if it's not crystal clear. We also started integrating some supplier optimization features and improved address quality checks, plus added a DHL reference for tracking. And, of course, the active shipment count bug was a big one – it was showing 630 total shipments instead of the actual 55 in-process ones. That's the kind of bug that makes users lose trust instantly, so getting that fixed was a huge win.

The UI got a massive facelift too. I completely swapped the color scheme from a somewhat cold teal to a warmer yellow/orange palette across *all* templates. That was a bigger job than I anticipated, touching a lot of files. Beyond that, there was a ton of dashboard cleanup: removing stale UI elements, fixing the logo, merging some scattered billing sections into one coherent view, and adding a date range filter. I also polished up the styles with lighter shadows and accent borders, and made the nav bar consistent and less bloated. Oh, and added an "insights verdict banner" – a little summary of key takeaways at the top.

The biggest struggle, hands down, was the fallout from reorganizing the `scripts/` directory into subdirectories. That broke *all* the import paths. It was one of those "why did I do this to myself?" moments, spending hours just fixing paths. It felt like playing whack-a-mole. Debugging the active shipment count was also tricky; it was a subtle filtering issue, not an obvious data error, which always takes longer to pinpoint. And honestly, the sheer volume of cleanup – archiving dead code, fixing `.gitignore`, cleaning temp files – just highlighted how quickly technical debt can accumulate if you're not vigilant. The color scheme swap, while visually satisfying, was also a bit of a grind, making sure every single element respected the new palette.

It felt really satisfying to tackle so much technical debt and improve the user experience so significantly. There were moments of frustration, especially with the import paths, but seeing the dashboard look cleaner and the data be more accurate makes it all worth it. It's a good reminder that sometimes the most impactful work isn't adding a flashy new feature, but refining what's already there and making it rock solid. It also reinforced the lesson that even small structural changes can have cascading effects, and planning refactors carefully is crucial. I'm definitely getting better at spotting those subtle data bugs too.

Next up: Diving deeper into predictive analytics for shipping routes.
